data.description:
Breer is a social enterprise that focuses on reducing the huge problem of food wastage in Hong Kong. The problem of food wastage and waste disposal has exponentially risen over the last decade, with the total amount of landfill space available almost used up. Breer is a revolution that helps solve this problem by reintroducing wasted or otherwise leftover bread into the supply chain by breaking it down into its raw ingredients and converting it into their own local craft beer. As we started our Good Seed Journey, we decided to speak to different stakeholders to understand their experiences. In an event organized by the Zubin Foundation,
we learnt that due to Covid-19, many ethnic minorities lost their job. Not only that, in our discussion with HKDA, we learnt that social interaction and integration has reduced since the pandemic. Owing to this, we decided to incorporate these two members as our key
beneficiaries, involving them in every step of the process. Now, Breer is the face of our business: our main aim is to foster inclusion and promote empowerment.

creator.mission: Research on Social Entrepreneurial Ecosystem in Hong Kong

data.description:
In 2012, a fund of HK$500 million was set up to catalyze the growth of social enterprises. The fund is the Social Innovation and Entrepreneurship Development Fund (the SIE Fund).
The Funds objective is to establish and support schemes and experiments with a view to attracting, inspiring, or nurturing social entrepreneurs to develop innovations that aim at creating social impact and social capital for the purpose of poverty relief in Hong Kong.
This research is conducted through the Good Seed Program, the earliest (started in 2015) and the main incubator for social startups funded by the SIE Fund. The program provides incubation and seed funding for early-stage social startups.
The research analyzed business proposals of 268 social startups in Hong Kong submitted to Good Seed Program, their survival status and critical incidents during the scaling processes revealed the roles of idiosyncratic and traditional ecosystem resource endowments including intermediary services, funding support, digital infrastructures, market infrastructures and public subsidies for social enterprise products and services, and institutional mechanisms such as shared discourse and values and arrangement

data.description: Mealingful is named after our motto, Making every meal meaningful. We strongly believe that every meal is meaningful. As the offspring and carer, we are very concerned about the quality of life of our elders, including the quality of food that they consume everyday. We hope that the elders could enjoy their meals, and be able to have their favorite dishes without limitations.

media.caption: Incubating cells
media.text: Cell nodes connect people cybernetically into small-word and global networks

pageContent.subText: The cell incubator will bring founders together to launch the first 10 cells through ixo.world. This will demonstrate how cyber-cellular organisations operate. Each cell will have an impact mission and implement at least one project, with accountable targets. Up to 100 applications will be accepted for the first cohort. The top 10 candidates will be invited to join the incubator. The work of this incubator will be considered done only after at least 8 of the teams have achieved their cell recruitment and project performance targets. On successful completion, cells will be rewarded with an economic stake in the ixo.world relayer node, valued at 5,000 Euro.
pageContent.subTitle: Mission
pageContent.text: The Cell Incubator connects a network of teams who are founding their own cells to implement pilot projects through ixo.world. A cyber-cell is a highly networked, intelligent form of organisation. This enables people to achieve a shared mission through self-coordination, self-governance, sharing common resources and having access to the same sources of truth. Cells mimic how nature operates in ways that are decentralised, self-regulating and adaptive. The human immune system is a great example. This organisational model is popular with high-performing teams. Now we can virtualise and augment cellular orgranisations with cybernetic capabilites, so that they can sense and respond much more rapidly and precisely to changes in the world. Members of the incubator cell will support each other to learn about, develop and implement cybernetic tools for their use-cases, using artificial intelligence, blockchain smart contracts, p2p communications, electronic rights and decentralised finance mechanisms.
pageContent.title: Incubating cells

data.longDescription: Cellular organisations (Cells) are a highly effective coordination mechanism for people to self-organise and self-govern towards achieving a common mission. By definition, cells are decentralised, autonomous, locally responsive, adaptable, hyper-networked, intelligent and purpose-driven. They are highly suitable for virtual and remote teams to work together and share common resources. [Learn more](https://github.com/ixofoundation/docs/blob/master/ixo/concepts/cell-nodes/README.md)

media.caption: People form a Cell to pursue a shared mission
media.text: People form a Cell to pursue a shared mission

pageContent.subText: Cell nodes are the digital infrastructure for all types of cellular organisations. These are decentralised, autonomous data stores with digital agency and cryptographic signing capabilities. Cell nodes enable data to be communicated quickly and securely through webs of trust. All participants in a cell have access to the same information and share intelligence both within their own cell node and with other organisations, through Internet of Impact networks.The digital artefacts created by a cell (such as Project Documents) are stored in the node as stateful records which are referenced in a distributed ledger. Public metadata are stored using the Interplanetary File System (IPFS). This allows cell nodes to retain a form of memory that can be stigmergically shared and rapidly amplified when cells need to be replicated or re-activated.

The ultimate goal is to foster an ecosystem where social entrepreneurs can thrive and innovative ideas, products and services can benefit society by meeting underserved needs, unleashing underutilised talents, promoting social inclusion, as well as enhancing the well-being and cohesion of the society.
data.name: The Social Innovation and Entrepreneurship Development Fund (SIE Fund)

data.description: Aging, loud noise, injury, stroke, infection, tumour, or inborn issue could result in hearing loss in different degrees. One of the easiest solutions to hearing loss is to wear a hearing aid. Hearing aids are electronics devices which can reproduce an amplified sound. There are different types and styles of hearing aids, such as Body-Worn (BW), Behind-The-Ear (BTE), Receiver-In-Canal (RIC), In-The-Ear (ITE), In-The-Canal (ITC), Completely-In-Canal (CIC), and Invisible-In-Canal (IIC). Traditional hearing aids are using analog circuits to simply amplify the sound while most of the modern hearing aids are using digital signal processing (DSP) to give advanced features like frequency shift, noise suppression and echo reduction.
data.imageDescription: To improve hearing aid users the ability to hear higher quality sound

data.description: Research Project by Norah Wang et. al.
data.imageDescription: In 2012, a fund of HK$500 million was set up to catalyze the growth of social enterprises. The fund is the Social Innovation and Entrepreneurship Development Fund (the SIE Fund). The Funds objective is to establish and support schemes and experiments with a view to attracting, inspiring, or nurturing social entrepreneurs to develop innovations that aim at creating social impact and social capital for the purpose of poverty relief in Hong Kong. This research is conducted through the Good Seed Program, the earliest (started in 2015) and the main incubator for social startups funded by the SIE Fund. The program provides incubation and seed funding for early-stage social startups. The research analyzed business proposals of 268 social startups in Hong Kong submitted to Good Seed Program, their survival status and critical incidents during the scaling processes revealed the roles of idiosyncratic and traditional ecosystem resource endowments including intermediary services, funding support, digital infrastructures, market infrastructures and public subsidies for social enterprise products and services, and institutional mechanisms such as shared discourse and values and arrangement
data.name: Social Entrepreneurial Ecosystem in Hong Kong

The fund is the Social Innovation and Entrepreneurship Development Fund (the SIE Fund). The Funds objective is to establish and support schemes and experiments with a view to attracting, inspiring, or nurturing social entrepreneurs to develop innovations that aim at creating social impact and social capital for the purpose of poverty relief in Hong Kong. This research is conducted through the Good Seed Program, the earliest (started in 2015) and the main incubator for social startups funded by the SIE Fund. The program provides incubation and seed funding for early-stage social startups. The research analyzed business proposals of 268 social startups in Hong Kong submitted to Good Seed Program, their survival status and critical incidents during the scaling processes revealed the roles of idiosyncratic and traditional ecosystem resource endowments including intermediary services, funding support, digital infrastructures, market infrastructures and public subsidies for social enterprise products and services, and institutional mechanisms such as shared discourse and values and arrangement
data.name: Social Entrepreneurial Ecosystem in Hong Kong

media.text: Alpha-bonds are an innovation for funding access to educational technologies

pageContent.subText: The ixo foundation is undertaking a multi-year research program on innovative financing to rapidly scale proven interventions that improve the quality of primary education. This project is part of a series of technology experiments using the ixo protocol and alpha-bonds.
pageContent.subTitle: Research Objective
pageContent.text: India has made enormous progress in education to achieve a 99% rate of primary school access. The Sustainable Development Goals have now focused attention on improving the quality of education to ensure that children in school are actually learning. A typical student in India is at least two grades behind the level expected for their age in literacy and numeracy. The Quality Education India Development Impact Bond (DIB) programme supports Indian education providers to improve learning outcomes for primary school children through an innovative results-based funding mechanism.
pageContent.title: Development Impact Bonds for Education

data.shortDescription: Innovative financing for scaling learning outcomes from quality primary education programmes.
